Test request
{quote}
Hello
Let us find a issue tracking software{quote}

When a person upgrades from Standard to Professional or Standard to Enterprise it always displays the same message:
{panel}
h2. {color:blue}Update License{color}
Update your license to a valid Enterprise license. You cannot run JIRA Enterprise with a JIRA Professional license.

You must provide a valid Administrator username and password and a valid JIRA Enterprise License 
{panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8614].
  {panel}

It bothers the heck out of me that I cannot use Browse functionality to search through my file folders to select the appropriate backup/restore or import file. I always have to remember the correct file path. etc. This bothered me recently when I was thinking about importing in a bunch of issues from an external system and realized that I had put it in a location that I could easily type rather than being able to just browse for it. 

Or am  I missing something here...? Help, please :-) How does everyone else do this without being able to browse your file system?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8605].
  {panel}

Would it be possible to add a boolean field isWatched to RemoteIssue and to the RSS feed returned from the navigator?

For jira-dashboard i would like to add a watched decorator to issues that are being watched.  This flag would also allow me to add a watch/unwatch action.  Currently I have no way of knowing if an issue is already being watched by the user, so the action can't be context sensitive.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8599].
  {panel}

It would be useful to have the ability to add a pluggable validator/condition/function for all issue operations (i.e. Edit, Assign, Clone, etc.) - as is done with the workflow actions (e.g. Start Progress, Resolve Issue).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
*NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8580].
{panel}
{panel:title=Atlassian Update - 8 September 2016|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ebf2f9|titleBGColor=#ebf2f9|bgColor=#ffffff}
Hi everyone,

CSV export from the issue navigator is now available for JIRA Cloud and [JIRA Server 7.2|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjira/jira-platform-releases/jira-7-2-x-platform-release-notes].

Dave Meyer
 Senior Product Manager, JIRA
{panel}
Users should be able to do a CSV export from the issue navigator in a way that would be compatible with the CSV Importer. In that way, it'd then be *possible* to merge JIRA instances and also make exporting to reporting tools more seamless.

At the moment, there's no such compatibility, e.g. comments in each issue need to be concatenated and moved to separate columns in order to be imported back with the CSV Importer.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8576].
  {panel}

More often than not when voting on an issue I also add it to my watch list so I can recieve notifications/updates.

It would be nice to be able to have an option (perhaps against each users profile) to enable issues to be automatically added to my watch list when voting on an issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8556].
  {panel}

It isn't possible to delete the default statuses (ie: Resolved or Reopened).  They are referenced by the read-only jira workflow and so are never inactive and thus can never be deleted.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8546].
  {panel}

The jelly AddComment class modifies a comments created date if the user has specified the date in the jelly tag. At the moment it grabs the comment with the most recent create date and modifies it. This could potentially be a bad thing, we could run into some concurrency issues, this should instead get the specific comment it is looking for (by id). This may be a bit tricky since the jelly tag uses the front-end action to create the value.
